[[ja:%E5%B0%8F%E5%B9%A1%E9%95%B7%E5%A1%9A%E5%8F%A4%E5%A2%B3]] [[sn:Obata Nagatsuka Kofun]]

{{afc comment|1=See [[Category:Pages using infobox ancient site with unknown parameters]] as this is a member[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 22:44, 22 April 2025 (UTC)}} [[Category:Marked infobox kofun with unknown parameters]][[Category:Secondary Marked infobox kofun with unknown parameters]][[Category:Secondary Marked infobox kofun with unknown parameters]][[Category:Secondary Marked infobox kofun with unknown parameters]] {{Japanese Kofun |Name=Obata Nagatsuka Kofun (小幡長塚古墳) |image={{ill|File:Obata-Nagatsuka-kofun01.jpg|de|Datei:Obata-Nagatsuka-kofun01.jpg|ja|File:Obata-Nagatsuka-kofun01.jpg|lt=250px|lt_ja=250px|lt_de=250px}} |image caption=Obata Nagatsuka Kofun {{ill|National Land Aerial Photograph|de|Nationale Luftaufnahme|ja|国土航空写真}} |Location={{ill|Aichi Prefecture|de|Aichi-Präfektur|ja|愛知県}} {{ill|Nagoya City|de|Stadt Nagoya|ja|名古屋市}} {{ill|Moriyama Ward|de|Bezirk Moriyama|ja|守山区}} Obata 4‑chome area |Coordinates={{WikiCoord2DMS|35|12|25.46|N|136|58|59.89|E}} |Shape=Keyhole‑shaped tumulus (Zenpō‑kōen‑fun, 前方後円墳) |Scale=Tumulus length approximately 81 m, front section width approximately 42 m, rear circular section diameter approximately 38 m |Date of construction=Early 6th century |Burial facility= |Buried individual= |Excavated items=Sue ware, figurative haniwa |Historic Site designation= |Notes= }}
'''Obata Nagatsuka Kofun''' (おばたながつかこふん) is a {{ill|Kofun|de|Kofun|ja|古墳}} located in {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|de|Aichi-Präfektur|ja|愛知県}} {{ill|Nagoya City|de|Stadt Nagoya|ja|名古屋市}} {{ill|Moriyama Ward|de|Bezirk Moriyama|ja|守山区}}. Locally, it is simply known as '''Nagatsuka Kofun'''.
== Overview == It is one of the kofun scattered around the Obatagahara area and is a {{ill|Keyhole‑shaped tumulus|de|Schlüssellochgrabhügel|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun}}. The surrounding area was used from the late Meiji period onward as the Obatagahara firing range by the {{ill|Imperial Japanese Army|de|Kaiserlich Japanische Armee|ja|大日本帝国陸軍|lt=Army|lt_ja=陸軍|lt_de=Armee}}, and traces of {{ill|trench|de|Schützengraben|ja|塹壕}} dug during military exercises still remain on the mound. Although the tumulus was once surrounded by a double moat, postwar development led to the demolition of the outer embankment and the complete infilling of the moats. Nowadays, houses are built densely right up to the side of the mound. The mound itself is preserved as Kitayama Park, a green space managed by Nagoya City.
== Scale and Structure == The main axis is oriented at 30.5° northwest, with the tumulus mound measuring approximately 81 meters in length, an estimated front section width of about 42 meters with a height of 5.5 meters, and an estimated rear circular section diameter of about 38 meters with a height of 6.5 meters. As mentioned earlier, because houses have been built close to the mound, a detailed survey of its lower portion (including the inner moat) has not been carried out, and the dimensions are not definitively established. Recent surveys have yielded figures of approximately 74 meters in mound length, 48 meters for the front section width, and 42 meters for the rear circular section diameter. It is also estimated to have been built in two tiers, and on the northeast side of the neck region there appears to be evidence of a {{ill|projection|de|Ausladung|ja|造り出し}}. No {{ill|excavation survey|de|Ausgrabungsuntersuchung|ja|発掘調査}} has been conducted on the mound, so its internal structure remains unknown. {{ill|fukiishi|de|Bedeckungssteine|ja|葺石}} have not been confirmed.
== burial goods == Many items have been excavated from near the outer embankment of the moat by the neck region, but most are fragments; the excavation conditions suggest that they may have been deliberately destroyed at a later date. The recovery of a figurative haniwa representing a person is a first among the kofun in Nagoya City. In addition, bullets believed to be from the {{ill|Type 38 infantry rifle|de|Type 38 Infanteriegewehr|ja|三八式歩兵銃}} have also been excavated, and these items are stored at the {{ill|Nagoya City Mishidai Archaeological Museum|de|Nagoya City Mishidai Archäologisches Museum|ja|見晴台遺跡#名古屋市見晴台考古資料館|lt=Nagoya City Mishidai Archaeological Museum|lt_ja=名古屋市見晴台考古資料館|lt_de=Mishidai Archäologisches Museum}}.
* Sue ware (high‑fired, jar‑shaped) * Cylindrical haniwa * Morning glory‑shaped haniwa * Figurative haniwa (fragments of arms and hands) * House‑shaped haniwa * Animal haniwa (such as waterfowl)
== References == * "Nagatsuka Kofun Excavation Survey Report" – Edited by Nagoya City Mishidai Archaeological Museum, published by {{ill|Nagoya City Board of Education|de|Bildungsbehörde Nagoya|ja|名古屋市教育委員会}}, 2006 (Heisei 19) * "Report on Buried Cultural Property Survey 55" – Edited by Nagoya City Mishidai Archaeological Museum, published by {{ill|Nagoya City Board of Education|de|Bildungsbehörde Nagoya|ja|名古屋市教育委員会}}, 2007 (Heisei 20) * "Nagatsuka Kofun Third Excavation Survey On‑site Briefing Materials" – Nagoya City Mishidai Archaeological Museum, 2009 (Heisei 22)
== Access == * {{ill|Nagoya Railroad|de|Nagoya Railroad|ja|名古屋鉄道|lt=Meitetsu|lt_ja=名鉄|lt_de=Meitetsu}} {{ill|Seto Line|de|Seto‑Linie|ja|名鉄瀬戸線|lt=Seto Line|lt_ja=瀬戸線|lt_de=Seto‑Linie}} – Approximately a 7‑minute walk from {{ill|Kitayama Station (Aichi)|de|Kitayama Bahnhof (Aichi)|ja|喜多山駅 (愛知県)|lt=Kitayama Station|lt_ja=喜多山駅|lt_de=Kitayama Bahnhof}}. * {{ill|Nagoya City Bus|de|Nagoya City Bus|ja|名古屋市営バス}} – Approximately an 8‑minute walk from the "Kitayama" bus stop.
== Related Articles == * {{ill|List of Japanese Kofun|de|Liste der japanischen Kofun|ja|日本の古墳一覧}}
